title: For Sale:  LAPD Winchester 94
postcontent:
LAPD Winchester Model 94 Caliber .30, serial # 811380. This Winchester was manufactured in 1916-17. Note on the left side of the butt stock it is stamped 77 – LAPD. Which means, 77 Precinct on 77th street in Los Angeles, CA. This rifle with saddle-ring was carried on foot petrol and on horseback. The lands and groves in the barrel are like new. 

The 77 Precinct was established in 1925. How the Winchester ended up in the publics hand I do not know. Perhaps the LAPD had an auction at a time when they were modernizing their equipment. I purchased the gun at Kerr’s Gun Shop, in El Reno, Oklahoma and I have had it approximately twenty years.

Anyone interested in this unique part of LA law enforcement history please call or Email.

title: For Sale:  LAPD Winchester Model 94 Caliber .30
postcontent:
LAPD Winchester Model 94 Caliber .30, serial # 811380. This Winchester was manufactured in 1916-17. Note on the left side of the butt stock it is stamped 77 – LAPD. Which means, 77 Precinct on 77th street in Los Angeles, CA. This rifle with saddle-ring was carried on foot petrol and on horseback. The lands and groves in the barrel are like new. 

The 77 Precinct was established in 1925. How the Winchester ended up in the publics hand I do not know. Perhaps the LAPD had an auction at a time when they were modernizing their equipment. This is Smith & Wesson’s model 5906, 9mm caliber Adjustable Sight variant, the highest form that a standard production model 59 descendant reached, with third / rounded trigger guard configuration. Product code was 108170, feature abbreviations were 15 SH AS AM TDA, for 15 shot magazine, Adjustable Sights, Ambidextrous Safety / Decocker, Traditional Double Action. This variant was produced in relatively small numbers from 1992 until 1999. THF Serial Number Prefix dates this pistols to 1992 - 1993 production. This specimen served in corporate security at the Grand Gulf Nuclear Plant in Port Gibson, Mississippi. Construction is stainless steel, with classic satin stainless .260 serrated spur hammer and matching .304 smooth combat trigger. Sights are distinctive S&W Wing protected, mill mated adjustable 2 rear and dovetailed black anodized front. This pistol has been professionally reworked, bead blast refinished, and test fired by Black Ice Coatings in Utah. Residual detractions are negligible as the photos will show. Grips are new factory Smith & Wesson. Magazines are both later production, orange follower 15 round Law Enforcement magazines from the ban period that ended in 2005. Bore, chamber, and mechanism are all bright, clean, and excellent, note that bushing contact evidence on the muzzle area of the barrel is only moderate. We estimate that this 5906 has been fired fewer than 1000 rounds, annual qualification. The distinctive configuration of the 4 inch barrel and the full-length stainless steel guide rod made these among the most accurate 9mms ever produced. Construction is entirely stainless steel, with the exception of black anodized sights and internal springs. Weight empty is 37 1/2 ounces. title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson .40 model 4046 Stainless Steel Frame DAO 3 Dot 12 Shot 2 Magazines VG Milwaukee County Sheriff Dept
postcontent:
Our # HG4046U

Photos are representative, but buyers will receive a virtually identical specimen to the one in the photos. From its tour of duty in Wisconsin with the Milwaukee County Sheriff’s Department comes this Smith & Wesson model 4046 Steel Frame Stainless Double Action Only pistol. The 4046, of course, came into production at the request of Law Enforcement agencies who demanded a strong well balanced pistol for transitioning officers accustomed to revolvers. From its VYK serial number prefix, it was manufactured in the late 90's. Manufacturer was Smith & Wesson; product code was 102955. Construction is entirely stainless steel, except for the black anodized .304 smooth faced combat trigger and .280 bobbed hammer. Sights are 3 dot Novak type, dovetailed into the slide. The 4046, of course, is full time double action. Its safeties consist in its firing pin safety and magazine safety, those guard against firing if the pistol is dropped, and will not permit firing without a magazine. Trigger pull is a very smooth motion of approximately 12 pounds. Barrel length is 4 inch classic bell nose muzzle that locks into place consistently; and with a  matching stainless full length guide rod. These elements made 3rd Generation S&Ws incredibly accurate. Magazine capacity is 11 + 1, and this pistol comes with two ban-period Law Enforcement marked 11 shot high capacity magazines. Weight empty is a superbly balanced 39 1/2 ounces with center of gravity at the trigger guard to grip frame junction. title: For Sale/Trade:  Luger-1936 S/42 made by Mauser
postcontent:
This is a very scarce early Pre-WWII German Luger manufactured by the Mauser factory. This was the first year that Germany stopped using the secret letter code markings for the year of manufacture on small arms. The chamber area is stamped "1936" and the front toggle is marked "S/42", the wartime code for the Mauser factory. The right side of the barrel extension has the early double "Eagle/63" Waffenamt proofs. It is numbered in the military fashion with the full serial number stamped on the major components and the last two digits on the various small parts. The grips are checkered walnut. 
Excellent overall with 95% of the original blue finish with wear on the edges and high spots overall with blue loss on the side plate, muzzle area front frame rails with a hint of thinning on the lower grips strap. The straw colors are vivid and remain 80% intact. The grips are excellent with nice original distinct checkering on both sides, mixed with some minor handling marks. This Luger has all matching upper serial numbers and all matching lower serial numbers as is normal for a Mauser produced luger made in 1936 and referenced in the information noted in the Gun Digest article below. 

The Luger Pistol
From Gun Digest Book, 11th Edition, 1957.
By: Fred A. Datig | April 20, 2009
The 1936 was the last year that Mauser used the traditional straw bluing on the small parts. Wartime production was starting up and demand required that the trigger, thumb safety, locking lever magazine release were converted to salt bluing in early 1937. Pre WWII manufacture means it was made as good as they ever were.
Beginning in 1936 Krieghoff, like Mauser, dated his products with the year of manufacture in numbers. A few examples may be encountered bearing dates of “1936″ and “1937″ which do not conform to the proper serial number range. These were pieces assembled from already numbered surplus parts at those later dates. These will have the 1936 S/42 upper all matching and all lower all matching. Some of the Mauser-made Lugers will be found bearing not only the commercial Mauser Banner but also carrying a date-stamp over the chamber. Such arms were originally intended for commercial sale, but when the German military forces demanded more Lugers than normal Mauser production could supply, pistols previously set aside for the commercial market were merely stamped with a date and accepted by the Army as regular issue weapons. In 1936 the secret code names were augmented. Mauser was assigned the code number “42″ in addition to the “S/42″ already in use. 

It is not unusual, then, to find Lugers bearing the code name “S/42″ and, for example, the date “1936,” and also to encounter “42″ pieces having the same date. To add to the confusion, pieces were also produced bearing the same date, “1936,” and inscribed with the commercial Mauser Banner. 
The Luger Pistol
From Gun Digest Book, 11th Edition, 1957.
By: Fred A. Datig | April 20, 2009
Editor’s Note: This is a sample article from Gun Digest Research, where you  can search thousands of archived Gun Digest Annual Book archives. To learn more go to http://research.gundigest.com.

title: For Sale:  Colt M1A1 1911 US ARMY WWII
postcontent:
Colt built this under government contract in 1941. As far as I can tell, it is completely original except for the barrel and grips. However, the barrel was manufactured by High Standard which was under contract during the war to make barrels. The grips are Colt but plain plastic grips were standard at the time. These are checkered walnut with the Colt medallion and in great shape. The pistol retains much of its original bluing. After 1941 all M1A1's were parkerized. The serial number on the frame and slide match. The pistol certainly shows its age and use but is totally functional. It undoubtedly saw some action. 
Included with the 1911 is a period US holster Made by Sears.  
Harriguns
